  "text": "The alerting evaluation scheduler tick and overrun detection are implemented across two files in grafana/grafana:\n\n1. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/schedule.go** — Contains the core scheduler logic:\n   - `Run` (line 175): Entry point that creates the ticker and calls `schedulePeriodic`.\n   - `schedulePeriodic` (line 246): The main tick loop. On each tick from the ticker channel, it records `BehindSeconds` (how far the scheduler is behind wall clock time via `sch.metrics.BehindSeconds.Set(start.Sub(tick).Seconds())`), calls `processTick`, and observes the total duration via `SchedulePeriodicDuration`.\n   - `processTick` (line 276): Determines which alert rules are ready to run on the current tick and dispatches them.\n   - `runJobFn` (line 426): Sends each scheduled evaluation to its rule evaluation routine. This is where overrun detection happens: if `ruleRoutine.Eval` returns a non-nil `dropped` value (meaning the routine's channel was full because the previous evaluation had not finished), it logs `sch.log.Warn(\"Tick dropped because alert rule evaluation is too slow\", ...)` and increments the `EvaluationMissed` counter.\n\n2. **pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/ticker/ticker.go** — Implements the `T` ticker struct whose `run` goroutine emits ticks at regular `baseInterval` marks without dropping them (unlike `time.Ticker`). The ticker queues ticks so the scheduler can detect how many cycles have been missed, which is the mechanism enabling overrun detection downstream."
}

